oreProperty(\\\"os.name\\\", originalOsName);\\n            restoreProperty(\\\"java.awt.headless\\\", originalHeadless);\\n            window.dispose();\\n        }\\n    }\\n\\n    private static void restoreProperty(String name, String value) {\\n        if (value == null) {\\n            System.clearProperty(name);\\n        }\\n        else {\\n            System.setProperty(name, value);\\n        }\\n    }\\n\\n    public static final class PeerBackedWindow extends Window {\\n        private static final long serialVersionUID = 1L;\\n\\n        private final AlphaPeer peer = new AlphaPeer();\\n\\n        private PeerBackedWindow() {\\n            super((Frame) null);\\n        }\\n\\n        @Override\\n        public boolean isDisplayable() {\\n            return true;\\n        }\\n\\n        public AlphaPeer getPeer() {\\n            return peer;\\n        }\\n    }\\n\\n    public static final class AlphaPeer {\\n        private float alpha = 1.0f;\\n\\n        public void setAlpha(float alpha) {\\n            this.alpha = alpha;\\n        }\\n    }\\n}\\n\"}\n2458:[recv] {\"type\": \"message_end\", \"message\": {\"role\": \"assistant\", \"content\": [{\"type\": \"thinking\", \"thinking\": \"**Considering Native Image Issues**\\n\\nI’m exploring the potential of constructing a window with a Linux OS and how this interacts with Mac settings. There’s a concern about class loading and JUnit imports, as well as the Native Image issue where classes might initialize at build time, which could ignore runtime properties. I’m considering adding a properties file to control initialization, but I’m cautious about possible breaks in functionality. I need to weigh the necessity of this change carefully.\\n\\n**Examining Class Initialization**\\n\\nI believe classes typically initialize at runtime, except for some from the JDK that might initialize early due to analysis. I need to consider whether I should reset `WindowUtils.Holder`, especially if the test order impact